123
14:42.639 --> 14:49.040
is still extremely important to the history of quantum computing because it provided the spark that got others

124
14:49.040 --> 14:53.680
thinking about larger, more sophisticated quantum algorithms.

125
14:53.680 --> 15:01.360
This includes a multicubit extension of Deutsch's algorithm that demonstrates a much more impressive quantum advantage.

126
15:01.360 --> 15:08.880
This is called the Deutsch Josa algorithm. It solves a similar problem, but in this case, the blackbox function

127
15:08.880 --> 15:15.519
that we want to learn about takes n bits as an input and outputs a single bit. As

128
15:15.519 --> 15:23.440
before, we're promised that the function is either constant, meaning the output bit is always one or always zero,

129
15:23.440 --> 15:29.519
regardless of the input bit string, or balanced, meaning the output is zero for

130
15:29.519 --> 15:35.839
half of the input bit strings and one for the other half. There are, of course, other

131
15:35.839 --> 15:42.800
functions that take n bits to a single bit that are neither constant nor balanced. But in this problem, we're

132
15:42.800 --> 15:49.759
promised that none of those functions are inside the black box. The one in the box is guaranteed to be either constant

133
15:49.759 --> 15:57.600
or balanced. The Deutsch Joseph circuit looks similar to Deutsche's algorithm, but with more cubits. Here we have an

134
15:57.600 --> 16:05.440
implementation of the Deutsch Jose algorithm to learn about a threebit function. This time we have three cubits

135
16:05.440 --> 16:13.839
for the input state rather than just the one. And then we have this last cubit for the output state. As before, again

136
16:13.839 --> 16:19.920
we prepare all the input cubits to be in the state 0 + one and the output cubit

137
16:19.920 --> 16:27.519
to be in the state 0 minus one. Then although the math is a little more complicated to follow, the principle

138
16:27.519 --> 16:34.480
remains the same. If the function is constant, it will not depend on the top three cubits at all. So their states

139
16:34.480 --> 16:42.920
will transform back to zero after the second hatomards and our measurement will yield a threebit string of all

140
16:42.920 --> 16:50.320
zeros. But if the function is balanced then when we measure the cubits following the hatoms the phase kickback

141
16:50.320 --> 16:57.199
mechanism will cause one or more of those bits to be one. That might not be so easy to see this time but if you work

142
16:57.199 --> 17:03.839
through each step yourself you'll soon see this must be the case. One way to check this is to try to calculate the

143
17:03.839 --> 17:10.959
probability of measuring all zeros with a balanced function. You should get a probability of zero. Let's run the

144
17:10.959 --> 17:17.839
Deutsch Josa algorithm on a quantum computer with Qiskit. The toughest step is probably creating the Deutsch Joseph

145
17:17.839 --> 17:25.199
function. That will be our black box that we query here. This code produces a random Deutsch Joseph function that is

146
17:25.199 --> 17:32.559
guaranteed to be either balanced or constant. Then we make our Deutsch Joseph circuit inserting our black box

147
17:32.559 --> 17:40.320
function here. Again, we run the circuit with sampler and after we measure, we look at

148
17:40.320 --> 17:44.080
the measured bits to determine whether the function was balanced or constant.

149
17:44.080 --> 17:52.080
If they're all zero, it's constant. But if there's at least one one bit in the string, then it's balanced. In this

150
17:52.080 --> 17:56.080
case, we get a bit string of 1 one one.

151
17:56.080 --> 18:03.679
So, we know that the function was balanced. I hope I've given you your first glimpse at how quantum algorithms

152
18:03.679 --> 18:10.200
can take advantage of interesting and often subtle quantum phenomena to obtain their advantage over classical

153
18:10.200 --> 18:18.160
algorithms. You've probably also picked up on how tricky it can be to design quantum algorithms. Even the very first

154
18:18.160 --> 18:26.320
one required a lot of creativity to achieve just a modest win over classical methods. And since that first algorithm,

155
18:26.320 --> 18:32.960
physicists and computer scientists have continued to come up with incredibly inventive ways to use quantum mechanics

156
18:32.960 --> 18:40.720
to their advantage, including further extensions and applications of the Deutsch Josa algorithm. If you want to

157
18:40.720 --> 18:47.120
learn about some of these, as well as try out the Deutsch and Deutsch Josa algorithms for yourself, head over to

